Open your file number in NJEMS and do the following:
BN3 <fieldset class="hide step19 option1111121111111211">
<legend><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 3. </b></legend>
<br/>Open your file number in NJEMS and do the following:
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BN3_1" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
<label for="xxx2BN3_1">1. Click on Activity Tracking, under the [pending] WFD/Coastal Wetlands application. Enter today's date for "PM Start Technical Review". </label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BN3_2" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
<label for="xxx2BN3_2">2. Check that the X/Y coordinates of the site and lot and block are accurate in NJEMS. </label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BN3_3" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
<label for="xxx2BN3_3">3. WFD/Coastal Wetlands application deadlines (45th or 90th day) should be identified and clearly labeled on the pre-review sheet and on the front cover of the file.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BN3_4" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
<label for="xxx2BN3_4">4. Search the file number in NJEMS to see if there are any previously issued determinations, authorizations, or violations onsite.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BN3_5" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
<label for="xxx2BN3_5">5. If historical aerials show that there was development onsite that may have needed wetlands authorizations, you can check Paradox, which contains information for authorizations prior to 2002. Otherwise, continue to WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 4.
  to conduct ArcGIS review.</label>
<br/>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_2BN31xxx" name="group_19" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_2BN31xxx">Continue to WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 4: ArcGIS Review.</label>

Paradox

He will provide you with login information.</span>

  <li>Password: firstinitiallastname ie: jsmith ;</li>
</ul>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BL4_2" />

<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BL4_3" />
<label for="xxx2BL4_3">3. Expand the Public Documents tab on the left hand side. Navigate down to Land Use and expand. Open Paradox.</label>
</br>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BL4_4" />
<label for="xxx2BL4_4">4. Choose your search method under the Title list. Searching by block-lot and county-municipality or by file number are the easiest ways to find your site. Enter the site information and click "run request". If there are approvals on the site, a report
  will be generated which details the file number, site location, permit type, owner, and program manager. Use this information to locate the file if necessary.</label>
</br>

ArcGIS
BJ5 <fieldset class="hide step21 option111112111111121121">
<legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 4: ArcGIS Review.</b></legend>
<p>Open ArcGIS. <span class="tooltiptext">A layer file containing all the data needed to conduct permit pre-review can be found at V:\lum\LUR\Pre-Review-Templates. (You can also use USGS Topoquads found in the "Imagery" category in DEP Data.)</span></p>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BJ5_1" />
<label for="xxx2BJ5_1">1. Enter the site X/Y coordinates and turn on the Parcels (block and lot) layer. Zoom-to your site.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BJ5_2" />
<label for="xxx2BJ5_2">2. USE ArcGIS and Pictometry to look at the land use over the last few decades. If there has been a change of land use without permit authorization, there may be potential for Land Use Enforcement action.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BJ5_3" />
<label for="xxx2BJ5_3">3. Apply the "Stream Network 2002" layer to check if a feature falls within your site or use the measure tool to see if a feature is within 300 feet.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BJ5_4" />
<label for="xxx2BJ5_4">4. Apply the "Surface Water Quality Standards" layer. Expand the table of contents to view the color coding system.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BJ5_5" />
<label for="xxx2BJ5_5">5. Apply the "Watersheds (DEPHUC14)" layer to see the water quality standards of the entire watershed. Identify the layer to see the name of the Watershed and Sub-watershed.</label>
<br/>
<p>
  Is there a Water feature onsite or within 300'?
</p>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_2BJ51" name="group_21" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_2BJ51">Yes!</label>
</p>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_2BJ52" name="group_21" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_2BJ52">No.</label>
</p>
</fieldset>

Stream Stats
BH6 <fieldset class="hide step22 option1111121111111211211">
<legend><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 5. </b></legend>
<p class="tooltip">Determine if the water feature drains more than 50 acres:<span class="tooltiptext">It is only necessary to check stream stats when there is a small headwater stream or ditch onsite and the 50 acre threshold is essential to determine if FHA regulations will apply. Use your best judgement of the location of the site in the watershed to determine if stream stats needs to be consulted or not. Sometimes stream stats is consulted AFTER a field visit when a feature is encountered that wasn't obvious on GIS.</span></p>
<input type="button" onclick="openStreamStats()" name="streamStatsBtn" value="Open Stream Stats" class="li">
<input type="button" onclick="openStreamStatsSOP()" name="streamStatsSOPBtn" value="Stream Stats Guidance">
<br/>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BH6_1" />
<label for="xxx2BH6_1">1. Use USGS Stream Stats to check if the water feature drains over 50 acres.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BH6_2" />
<label for="xxx2BH6_2">2. Document your findings from Stream Stats in your Application Review Form. Continue to Riparian Zones, below.</label>
<br/>
<p>
  Riparian zones are determined by geology of the site, presence of threatened and endangered species downstream, and surface water quality standards of the watershed.
</p>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BH6_3" />
<label for="xxx2BH6_3">All features draining more than 50 acres are regulated and have an associated flood hazard area and riparian zone. </label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BH6_4" />
<label for="xxx2BH6_4">Features draining less than 50 acres are regulated if the feature is not a ditch and has a defined bed and bank. These features do not have a flood hazard area, but do have a riparian zone.</label>
<br/>
<p>
  Does the site have a riparian zone?
</p>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_2BH6_1" name="group_22" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_2BH6_1">Yes!</label>
</p>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_2BH6_2" name="group_22" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_2BH6_2">No.</label>
</p>
</fieldset>

Riparian Zone Determination
BF7 <fieldset class="hide step23 option11111211111112112111">
<legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 6. </b> <span class="tooltiptext">A 150 foot riparian zone can also be attributed to a regulated water if there are critically dependent T&E species onsite or within one downstream mile.  Please see the T&E section for more information.</span></legend>
<br/>Determine the <b>riparian zone</b>:
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF7_1" />
<label for="xxx2BF7_1">300': Category One (C1) waters and all upstream tributaries within the same HUC14.
</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF7_2" />
<label for="xxx2BF7_2">150': Trout production waters and all upstream waters; Trout maintenance waters and all upstream waters within one linear mile; waters flowing through an area with acid producing soils; and waters with critically dependent T&E species.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF7_3" />
<label for="xxx2BF7_3">50': All other regulated features </label>
<br/>
<p>
  Document your findings in your Application Review Form. Continue to Threatened & Endangered (T&E) Species determination, below.
</p>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_2BF7_1" name="group_23" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_2BF7_1">Continue to Threatened & Endangered (T&E) Species</label>
</p>
</fieldset>

<label for="xxxU8_3">3. Identify the species of concern.</label>

T&E Part 2
T10 <fieldset class="hide step25 option11111211111112111111">
<legend><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP  7 (Continued):</b></legend>
<p>
  Open the file in NJEMS:

<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBG10_3" />
<label for="xxxBG10_3">3. From the list of Word Processing templates, select "<em>T&E Form CAF</em>." </label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBG10_4" />
<label for="xxxBG10_4" class="tooltip">4. Fill out form and print one copy. Save form to NJEMS.
  <span class="tooltiptext">Remember to add the "date permit was received", "date you sent the review to T&E." The 45th (GP) or 90th (IP) day deadline date should be clearly visible in large lettering on the form so the T&E staff knows to prioritize. Make sure that all permits with the application are noted.  (sometimes the automated document does not populate all this information on the form)</span>
</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBG10_5" />
<label for="xxxBG10_5">5. Activity Tracking: Add Row, select "Group Task" box, and select "T&E Species Habitat Review" from the drop down. Assign "PM Send T&E Review to T&E" unit to yourself. Assign all other tasks to appropriate T&E staff for your region.</label>
<br/>
<p>
  Deliver the review package to the T&E Unit (baskets sorted by permit type and geographic region located outside T&E unit cube area) containing:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>A copy of the T&E review form</li>
  <li>A copy of the LURP form;</li>
  <li>A USGS map or road map showing property location; and</li>
  <li>One copy of the plan. </li>
</ol>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_BG10_1" name="group_25" type="checkbox" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_BG10_1">I have sent the information to T&E.</label>
</p>
<p>
  <input id="xxxquestion_BG10_2" name="group_25" type="checkbox" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
  <label for="xxxquestion_BG10_2">Select "Yes, and I have sent the file information to T&E! (Continue to STEP 8)" under <b>Flood Hazard Area (FHA): STEP 7</b> (above).</label>
</p>
</fieldset>

U11 <fieldset class="hide step26 option1111121111111211211112">
<legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 9. </b></legend>
<p>
  EPA Jurisdiction:
</p>
<p>
  Check the proposed project for the following:
</p>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_1" />
<label for="xxxBH11_1">Discharge with potential for affecting endangered or threatened species.</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_2" />
<label for="xxxBH11_2">Discharges of dredged or fill material which have the potential for adverse impacts on the waters of a state other than New Jersey;</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_3" />
<label for="xxxBH11_3">Discharges known or suspected to contain toxic pollutants, hazardous substances, toxic substances, or hazardous waste;</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_4" />
<label for="xxxBH11_4">Discharges located in the proximity of a public water supply intake;</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_5" />
<label for="xxxBH11_5">Discharges within critical areas established under state or Federal law; including but not limited to:</label>
<ul>
  <li>A National or State forest,</li>
  <li>fish or wildlife sanctuary,</li>
  <li>National or historic monument,</li>
  <li>Wilderness area or preserve,</li>
  <li>A site identified or proposed under the National Historic Preservation Act; or</li>
  <li>A component of the National Wild and Scenic Rivers system.</li>
</ul>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_6" />
<label for="xxxBH11_6">The filling of five or more acres of freshwater wetlands or State open waters and/or any regulated activity which results in significant reductions in the ecological, commercial, or recreational values or five or more acres of freshwater wetlands or State
  open waters;</label>
<br/>
<input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_7" />
<label for="xxxBH11_7">Culvert enclosures of more than 100 feet
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_8" />
  <label for="xxxBH11_8">Channelization or more than 500 feet of a river or stream;</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBH11_9" />
  <label for="xxxBH11_9">Cutting more than 5 acres of trees in wetlands for airport site line clearing.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    A template letter is found at V:>lum>LUR>Pre-Review Resources>Transmittal sheets>USEPA Wotus Determination Request. The letter should be amended to include project specific details. Along with the letter, include the first page of DLUR application, the
    Permit and Database transmittal, a USGS location map and/or tax map, a copy of a plan that shows the wetland line, and any other supporting documents or site plans. Send packet to the attention of Bob Montgomerie: montgomerie.robert@epa.gov and copy
    Dan Montella: Montella.daniel@epa.gov.
  </p>
  <p>
    Does the proposed project have any of the above characteristics?

    Permit and Database transmittal, a USGS location map and/or tax map, a copy of a plan that shows the wetland line, and any other supporting documents or site plans. Send packet to the attention of Bob Montgomerie: montgomerie.robert@epa.gov and copy

EPA Priority Wetlands
S13 <fieldset class="hide step27 option11111211111112112111121">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 9. </b><span class="tooltiptext">For further assistance; you may use the guidance document on the EPA Priority Wetland Layer found at V:\lum\LUR\Pre-Review Resources\SOPs</span></legend>
  <p>
    To determine if the site has EPA priority wetlands, check the proposed project for the following:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxCR13_1" />
  <label for="xxxCR13_1" class="tooltip">Use the GIS Layer <span class="tooltiptext">found at V:\lum\LUR\GIS_Data\ EPA_Priority_Wetlands.lyr</span></label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxCR13_2" />
  <label for="xxxCR13_2">Use the Identify tool to see information, including caveats for wetlands that may fall in the geographic area but are excluded from the EPA priority.</label>
  <p>
    Soils:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxCR13_3" />
  <label for="xxxCR13_3">Use the DEP Data Soils (SSURGO) View layer to determine the soils that are mapped onsite.</label>
  <ul>
    <li> if soils that are "poorly drained" or "somewhat poorly drained" are mapped onsite, these areas that wetlands are most likely to occur and help narrow the focus of what to inspect in the field.</li>
    <li>The mapped soil type is also required for the Wetland Data Form</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_CR13_1" name="group_27" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_CR13_1">Continue to United States Fish & Wildlife Service (USFWS) Review</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

  <label for="xxxCR13_2">Use the Identify tool to see information, including caveats for wetlands that may fall in the geographic area but are excluded from the EPA priority.</label>
  <p>
    Soils:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxCR13_3" />
  <label for="xxxCR13_3">Use the DEP Data Soils (SSURGO) View layer to determine the soils that are mapped onsite.</label>
  <ul>
    <li> if soils that are "poorly drained" or "somewhat poorly drained" are mapped onsite, these areas that wetlands are most likely to occur and help narrow the focus of what to inspect in the field.</li>
    <li>The mapped soil type is also required for the Wetland Data Form</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_CR13_1" name="group_27" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_CR13_1">Continue to United States Fish & Wildlife Service (USFWS) Review</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

USFWS
P15 <fieldset class="hide step28 option111112111111121121111211">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 9. </b></legend>
  <p>
    Check Activity Tracking to see if a USFWS review request has been sent by ASU. If not, then the following screening should be done.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_1" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_1">To determine whether the pending wetland permit requires USFWS review, use the "Two-Way Memorandum USFWS/NJDEP Freshwater Wetlands Permit Application Review" form found in V:\lum\LUR\Pre-Review Resources\Transmittal Sheets.</label>
  <ul>
    <li>If your pending permit is not listed on the transmittal, then USFWS review is not required.</li>
    <li>If the permit is applicable, the PRO still needs to check if the municipality is listed in the "USFW Federally Listed and Candidate Species Occurrences in New Jersey by County and Municipality" packet found in V:\lum\LUR\Pre-Review Resources\FWW Resources.</li>
  </ul>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_2" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_2">If the permit is listed in the memorandum, and the project proposes disturbance to wetlands (not just transition area), and the municipality is listed in the packet, a USFWS review is required. The PRO should create a package containing:</label>
  <ol>
    <li>A copy of the LURP Permit Application Transmittal Form; </li>
    <li>A copy of the LURP form; </li>
    <li>A USGS map or road map showing property location; and</li>
    <li>One copy of the plan.</li>
  </ol>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_3" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_3">Place in the bin labeled USFW Review (North or South) located next to the T&E Unit.</label>
  <p>
    In NJEMS, complete the following in activity tracking:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_4" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_4">1. Add row, select group task, and select "Pre-review Send USFWS In-House Review to T&E." </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_5" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_5">2. Assign the "Pre-review Send USFWS In-House Review to T&E" task to yourself and add date requested, Assign the other tasks to Karena DiLeo and leave the dates blank.</label>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_2BF13_1" name="group_28" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_2BF13_1">Continue to State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

    <label for="xxxquestion_2BF13_1">Continue to State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review</label>

BK15 <fieldset class="hide step28 option11111211111112112112321">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 9. </b></legend>
  <p>
    Check Activity Tracking to see if a USFWS review request has been sent by ASU. If not, then the following screening should be done.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_1" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_1">To determine whether the pending wetland permit requires USFWS review, use the "Two-Way Memorandum USFWS/NJDEP Freshwater Wetlands Permit Application Review" form found in V:\lum\LUR\Pre-Review Resources\Transmittal Sheets.</label>
  <ul>
    <li>If your pending permit is not listed on the transmittal, then USFWS review is not required.</li>
    <li>If the permit is applicable, the PRO still needs to check if the municipality is listed in the "USFW Federally Listed and Candidate Species Occurrences in New Jersey by County and Municipality" packet found in V:\lum\LUR\Pre-Review Resources\FWW Resources.</li>
  </ul>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_2" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_2">If the permit is listed in the memorandum, and the project proposes disturbance to wetlands (not just transition area), and the municipality is listed in the packet, a USFWS review is required. The PRO should create a package containing:</label>
  <ol>
    <li>A copy of the LURP Permit Application Transmittal Form; </li>
    <li>A copy of the LURP form; </li>
    <li>A USGS map or road map showing property location; and</li>
    <li>One copy of the plan.</li>
  </ol>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_3" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_3">Place in the bin labeled USFW Review (North or South) located next to the T&E Unit.</label>
  <p>
    In NJEMS, complete the following in activity tracking:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_4" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_4">1. Add row, select group task, and select "Pre-review Send USFWS In-House Review to T&E." </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxx2BF13_5" />
  <label for="xxx2BF13_5">2. Assign the "Pre-review Send USFWS In-House Review to T&E" task to yourself and add date requested, Assign the other tasks to Karena DiLeo and leave the dates blank.</label>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_2BF13_1" name="group_28" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_2BF13_1">Continue to State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review</label>
  </p>

SHPO
M17 <fieldset class="hide step29 option1111121111111211211112111">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 10. </b><span class="tooltiptext">A SHPO review may be required for a Freshwater Wetland Permit or a Coastal Zone Management Permit that has historic archeological resources onsite. Aspects of a project that could affect SHPO resources are impacts to historic sites or buildings, historic neighborhoods and/or archeological resources.</span></legend><br/>
  <p>
    Use ArcGIS layers to identify any areas of historic value:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_1" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_1">Select the layer "Historic Preservation Data." Please be sure to check each of the sublayers under this layer (click on plus and check each of the four sublayers including Historic District, Historic Fill, Historic Site, and Historic Archeological Site
    Grid.) If any of these layers intersect the project site, then a SHPO review is required.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_2" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_2">If the project site exceeds 20 acres in size and includes a permanent water body (for example wetlands, pond, lake, river or perennial stream) or is located within 250 feet of a permanent water body; or</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_3" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_3">If the proposed projects includes a new, replacement, reconstructed, or rehabilitated bridge or culvert, a SHPO review is required.</label>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL17_1" name="group_29" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_BL17_1">A State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review is required.</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL17_2" name="group_29" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />

  <label for="xxxBL17_2">If the project site exceeds 20 acres in size and includes a permanent water body (for example wetlands, pond, lake, river or perennial stream) or is located within 250 feet of a permanent water body; or</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_3" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_3">If the proposed projects includes a new, replacement, reconstructed, or rehabilitated bridge or culvert, a SHPO review is required.</label>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL17_1" name="group_29" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_BL17_1">A State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review is required.</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL17_2" name="group_29" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_BL17_2">No State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review is required.</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>
EP17 <fieldset class="hide step29 option111112111111121111113111">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 10. </b><span class="tooltiptext">A SHPO review may be required for a Freshwater Wetland Permit or a Coastal Zone Management Permit that has historic archeological resources onsite. Aspects of a project that could affect SHPO resources are impacts to historic sites or buildings, historic neighborhoods and/or archeological resources.</span></legend><br/>
  <p>
    Use ArcGIS layers to identify any areas of historic value:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_1" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_1">Select the layer "Historic Preservation Data." Please be sure to check each of the sublayers under this layer (click on plus and check each of the four sublayers including Historic District, Historic Fill, Historic Site, and Historic Archeological Site
    Grid.) If any of these layers intersect the project site, then a SHPO review is required.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_2" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_2">If the project site exceeds 20 acres in size and includes a permanent water body (for example wetlands, pond, lake, river or perennial stream) or is located within 250 feet of a permanent water body; or</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL17_3" />
  <label for="xxxBL17_3">If the proposed projects includes a new, replacement, reconstructed, or rehabilitated bridge or culvert, a SHPO review is required.</label>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL17_1" name="group_29" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_BL17_1">A State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) Review is required.</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL17_2" name="group_29" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />

G19 <fieldset class="hide step30 option11111211111112112111121111">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 10. </b><span class="tooltiptext">A SHPO review may be required for a Freshwater Wetland Permit or a Coastal Zone Management Permit that has historic archeological resources onsite. Aspects of a project that could affect SHPO resources are impacts to historic sites or buildings, historic neighborhoods and/or archeological resources.</span></legend><br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL19_1" />
  <label for="xxxBL19_1">If a SHPO review is required, fill out the LURP Permit Application Transmittal Form and include the following:</label>
  <ol>
    <li>A copy of the LURP Permit Application Transmittal Form; </li>
    <li>A copy of the LURP form; </li>
    <li>A USGS map or road map showing property location; and</li>
    <li>One copy of the plan.</li>
  </ol>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL19_2" />
  <label for="xxxBL19_2">
    Deliver the package to the SHPO secretary at 501 East State St 4th Floor southwest corner or to the SHPO mail box bin the lunchroom.
  </label>
  <p>
    In NJEMS, the following should be completed in activity tracking:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL19_3" />
  <label for="xxxBL19_3">1. Add row, select group task, select SHPO referral. </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL19_4" />
  <label for="xxxBL19_4">2. Assign "Request Comments from SHPO" and "Receive SHPO comments" to yourself and add date requested.</label>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_BL19_1" name="group_30" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_BL19_1">Continue to check CAFRA</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

  <label for="xxxBL19_4">2. Assign "Request Comments from SHPO" and "Receive SHPO comments" to yourself and add date requested.</label>

DZ19 <fieldset class="hide step30 option1111121111111211111122111">
  <legend class="tooltip"><b>WFD & Coastal Wetlands IP: STEP 10. </b><span class="tooltiptext">A SHPO review may be required for a Freshwater Wetland Permit or a Coastal Zone Management Permit that has historic archeological resources onsite. Aspects of a project that could affect SHPO resources are impacts to historic sites or buildings, historic neighborhoods and/or archeological resources.</span></legend><br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL19_1" />
  <label for="xxxBL19_1">If a SHPO review is required, fill out the LURP Permit Application Transmittal Form and include the following:</label>
  <ol>
    <li>A copy of the LURP Permit Application Transmittal Form; </li>
    <li>A copy of the LURP form; </li>
    <li>A USGS map or road map showing property location; and</li>
    <li>One copy of the plan.</li>
  </ol>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxBL19_2" />
  <label for="xxxBL19_2">
    Deliver the package to the SHPO secretary at 501 East State St 4th Floor southwest corner or to the SHPO mail box bin the lunchroom.
  </label>
  <p>
    In NJEMS, the following should be completed in activity tracking:
  </p>

G21 <fieldset class="hide step31 option111112111111121121111211111">
  <legend><b> STEP 11: CAFRA check</b></legend>
  <p>
    Use the ArcGIS CAFRA layer to check if your site falls within the CAFRA zone. If any of the following conditions apply, a CAFRA permit is required:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_1" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_1">1. Check here if the project is located on a beach or dune.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_2" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_2">2. Check here if the project is within 150 feet and the first use landward of the MHWL and/or beach or dune.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_3" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_3">3. Check here if the project is a public development (landfills, sewer plants, highways, utility lines, airport)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_4" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_4">4. Check here if the project is an industrial development (power plant, manufacturing, factory, mining)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_5" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_5">5. Check here if the project within 500 feet of the MHWL and proposes 25 or more residential units or 50 or more parking spaces.<span class="tooltiptext">If yes, then a CAFRA permit is generally required.  The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality." which can be determined by checking the latest list at http://www.state.nj.us/dca/divisions/dlgs/resources/stateaidinfo.shtml. If the project municipality is listed, then the threshold for CAFRA jurisdiction is different and can be as much as 75 or more residential units or 150 or more parking spaces.  Please see N.J.A.C. 7:7-2.2(a)3 and 4 for more information.</span></label>
  <p>
    The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality."
  </p>
  <button onClick="openStateAidInfo()">Check for "qualifying municipality."</button>
  <br/>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_6" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_6">From the first drop down, select "Urban Aid Eligibility."</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_7" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_7">Select the <b>current fiscal year</b> from the second drop down.</label>
  <p>
    Is the project municipality listed?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_1" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AC21_1">Yes! (Continue to: Check Coastal Wetlands)</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_2" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AC21_2">No. (Continue to: Check Coastal Wetlands)</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

    Use the ArcGIS CAFRA layer to check if your site falls within the CAFRA zone. If any of the following conditions apply, a CAFRA permit is required:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_1" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_1">1. Check here if the project is located on a beach or dune.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_2" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_2">2. Check here if the project is within 150 feet and the first use landward of the MHWL and/or beach or dune.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_3" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_3">3. Check here if the project is a public development (landfills, sewer plants, highways, utility lines, airport)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_4" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_4">4. Check here if the project is an industrial development (power plant, manufacturing, factory, mining)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_5" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_5">5. Check here if the project within 500 feet of the MHWL and proposes 25 or more residential units or 50 or more parking spaces.<span class="tooltiptext">If yes, then a CAFRA permit is generally required.  The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality." which can be determined by checking the latest list at http://www.state.nj.us/dca/divisions/dlgs/resources/stateaidinfo.shtml. If the project municipality is listed, then the threshold for CAFRA jurisdiction is different and can be as much as 75 or more residential units or 150 or more parking spaces.  Please see N.J.A.C. 7:7-2.2(a)3 and 4 for more information.</span></label>
  <p>
    The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality."
  </p>
  <button onClick="openStateAidInfo()">Check for "qualifying municipality."</button>
  <br/>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_6" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_6">From the first drop down, select "Urban Aid Eligibility."</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_7" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_7">Select the <b>current fiscal year</b> from the second drop down.</label>
  <p>
    Is the project municipality listed?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_1" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AC21_1">Yes! (Continue to: Check Coastal Wetlands)</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_2" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AC21_2">No. (Continue to: Check Coastal Wetlands)</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_2" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_2">2. Check here if the project is within 150 feet and the first use landward of the MHWL and/or beach or dune.</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_3" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_3">3. Check here if the project is a public development (landfills, sewer plants, highways, utility lines, airport)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_4" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_4">4. Check here if the project is an industrial development (power plant, manufacturing, factory, mining)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_5" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_5">5. Check here if the project within 500 feet of the MHWL and proposes 25 or more residential units or 50 or more parking spaces.<span class="tooltiptext">If yes, then a CAFRA permit is generally required.  The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality." which can be determined by checking the latest list at http://www.state.nj.us/dca/divisions/dlgs/resources/stateaidinfo.shtml. If the project municipality is listed, then the threshold for CAFRA jurisdiction is different and can be as much as 75 or more residential units or 150 or more parking spaces.  Please see N.J.A.C. 7:7-2.2(a)3 and 4 for more information.</span></label>
  <p>
    The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality."
  </p>
  <button onClick="openStateAidInfo()">Check for "qualifying municipality."</button>
  <br/>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_6" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_6">From the first drop down, select "Urban Aid Eligibility."</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_7" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_7">Select the <b>current fiscal year</b> from the second drop down.</label>
  <p>
    Is the project municipality listed?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_1" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AC21_1">Yes! (Continue to: Check Coastal Wetlands)</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_2" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />

  <label for="xxxAC21_3">3. Check here if the project is a public development (landfills, sewer plants, highways, utility lines, airport)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_4" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_4">4. Check here if the project is an industrial development (power plant, manufacturing, factory, mining)</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_5" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_5">5. Check here if the project within 500 feet of the MHWL and proposes 25 or more residential units or 50 or more parking spaces.<span class="tooltiptext">If yes, then a CAFRA permit is generally required.  The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality." which can be determined by checking the latest list at http://www.state.nj.us/dca/divisions/dlgs/resources/stateaidinfo.shtml. If the project municipality is listed, then the threshold for CAFRA jurisdiction is different and can be as much as 75 or more residential units or 150 or more parking spaces.  Please see N.J.A.C. 7:7-2.2(a)3 and 4 for more information.</span></label>
  <p>
    The exception occurs when the project occurs within a "qualifying municipality."
  </p>
  <button onClick="openStateAidInfo()">Check for "qualifying municipality."</button>
  <br/>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_6" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_6">From the first drop down, select "Urban Aid Eligibility."</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAC21_7" />
  <label for="xxxAC21_7">Select the <b>current fiscal year</b> from the second drop down.</label>
  <p>
    Is the project municipality listed?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AC21_1" name="group_31" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />

Check Coastal Wetlands
E23 <fieldset class="hide step32 option1111121111111211211112111111">
  <legend><b> STEP 12: Check Coastal Wetlands</b></legend>
  <p class="tooltip">
    Use the ArcGIS "1970 Wetland Basemaps" layer to determine if your site has coastal wetlands.
    <span class="tooltiptext">The basemap can be found in the DEP data bar under "imagery" labeled as "1970 Wetlands Basemap".</span>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      It is not sufficient to use the "Upper Wetlands Boundary" layer on ArcGIS.
    </li>
    <li>
      Make sure that there is a mapped vegetation unit waterward of the upper wetland boundary (thick dark line) on the mapping.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Is there a mapped vegetation unit shown on the site?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AA23_1" name="group_32" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AA23_1">Yes! (Continue to: Tidelands Review)</label>
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AA23_2" name="group_32" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AA23_2">No. (Continue to: Tidelands Review)</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

      It is not sufficient to use the "Upper Wetlands Boundary" layer on ArcGIS.
    </li>
    <li>
      Make sure that there is a mapped vegetation unit waterward of the upper wetland boundary (thick dark line) on the mapping.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Is there a mapped vegetation unit shown on the site?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AA23_1" name="group_32" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AA23_1">Yes! (Continue to: Tidelands Review)</label>

BN23 <fieldset class="hide step32 option111112111111121121123211111">
  <legend><b> STEP 12: Check Coastal Wetlands</b></legend>
  <p class="tooltip">
    Use the ArcGIS "1970 Wetland Basemaps" layer to determine if your site has coastal wetlands.
    <span class="tooltiptext">The basemap can be found in the DEP data bar under "imagery" labeled as "1970 Wetlands Basemap".</span>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      It is not sufficient to use the "Upper Wetlands Boundary" layer on ArcGIS.
    </li>
    <li>
      Make sure that there is a mapped vegetation unit waterward of the upper wetland boundary (thick dark line) on the mapping.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Is there a mapped vegetation unit shown on the site?
  </p>

    <li>
      Make sure that there is a mapped vegetation unit waterward of the upper wetland boundary (thick dark line) on the mapping.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Is there a mapped vegetation unit shown on the site?
  </p>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AA23_1" name="group_32" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />

Tidelands
C25 <fieldset class="hide step33 option11111211111112112111121111111">
  <legend><b>STEP 13: Tidelands Review </b></legend>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxitem201" />
  <label for="xxxitem201" class="tooltip">1. Make sure there is a copy of the tideland's instrument for all work on natural waterways.
    <span class="tooltiptext">They need to at least submit proof that they have sent a letter or a request of tideland's interest. Show limits of Tidelands boundary on plans if license, lease, or grant is in effect.</span>
  </label>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Applications from the NJDEP do not require Tideland evidence.
    </li>
    <li>
      Lagoon work does not require Tidelands.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AE25_1" name="group_33" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AE25_1">Continue to: Wrap Up</label>
  </p>
</fieldset>

  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxitem201" />

    <span class="tooltiptext">They need to at least submit proof that they have sent a letter or a request of tideland's interest. Show limits of Tidelands boundary on plans if license, lease, or grant is in effect.</span>
  </label>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Applications from the NJDEP do not require Tideland evidence.
    </li>
    <li>
      Lagoon work does not require Tidelands.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <input id="xxxquestion_AE25_1" name="group_33" type="radio" onClick="scrollSmoothToBottom()" />
    <label for="xxxquestion_AE25_1">Continue to: Wrap Up</label>
  </p>

Wrap-up/NJEMS
C27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option111112111111121121111211111111">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>

  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
E27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option111112111111121121111211111211">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>

    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
L27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option11111211111112112111121112211">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>

  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
Q27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option111112111111121121111221111111">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>

  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
U27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option11111211111112112111122112121">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
