  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
EL27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option11111211111112111111321111121">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>

  </label>

  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>

  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>

  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
EP27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option1111121111111211111131112211">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>

EU27 <fieldset class="hide step34 option11111211111112111111311111221">
  <legend><b>STEP 14: Wrap Up</b></legend>
  <p>
    Wrap Up:
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_1" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_1">1. In Activity Tracking, whoever fills out the pre-review checklist (PRO or pre-reviewer) should assign "Start Technical Review" and "End Technical Review" to themselves and add the appropriate date.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_2" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_2">2. Add the checklist to NJEMS as a Blank Word Document (title the document "Pre Review.")</label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_3" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_3">3. If the pre-review PRO is not the lead reviewer on the project, then the file should be delivered to the lead reviewer with the checklist attached to the left side of the folder.</label>
  <br/>
  <p>
    Using LetterBuilder in NJEMS, begin writing the FHA Environmental Report. If the application contains more than the FHA, restart/refresh this page and check them accordingly.
  </p>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_4" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_4">
    a. If they request or plans show a bulkhead being replaced out shore of an existing bulkhead on a man made waterways they can not apply for a GP14. (It is an IP.)
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_5" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_5">
    b. All Bulkhead replacements on man made waterways using a GP14 must be rip out and replacements.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_6" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_6">
    c. Bulkhead replacement on natural waterways may be placed a maximum of 24" out under the GP14; but if there is any docks, piers or boatlifts requested all activities are reviewed under an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_7" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_7">
    d. If you are connecting bulkheads on either side of your property with a new bulkhead on a property that never had a bulkhead on any kind of waterway and the bulkhead is going at or above the MHWL the permit is a GP10.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_8" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_8">
    e. On a man made waterway if you are replacing the bulkhead and replacing or adding a dock or other structure in water they need two permits GP14 and GP19. This is an example of when there is NO fee discount
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_9" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_9">
    f. On a natural waterway if they are proposing any work below the MHWL all activities (i.e. docks, piers, boatlifts, and Jet Ski lifts) require an IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_0" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_0">
    g. All applications on Man Made Waterway go to the GP unit whether it is a GP or IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_11" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_11">
    h. All GP applications on Natural Waterways go to the GP Unit
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_12" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_12">
    i. All IP applications on Natural Waterways go to the Project Manager of that town unless in an Urban Growth area. In the Urban Growth area all IP's for docks and piers are assigned to Chris Jones and he will reassign them. All other type of work in Urban
    Growth area that requires any type of waterfront IP goes to the Urban Growth project manager assigned to that town.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_13" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_13">
    j. Work for areas upland of the mean high water line in the area of CAFRA jurisdiction is regulated under CAFRA. Work in an upland of a MHWL outside of CAFRA area (i.e. on the Hudson River) work would require an waterfront IP-Upland.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_14" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_14">
    k. No one can apply for a waterfront coastal GP and a Waterfront IP for work on the same site. All work must be approved under the IP. They could apply for a CAFRA coastal GP and a Waterfront IP. I.E. CAFRA GP 9 to rebuild a house and a Waterfront Development
    In-Water IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_15" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_15">
    l. There are two different types of COASTAL GP's. The waterfront GP's are for work not requiring an IP taking place waterward of the MHWL. There are also Coastal GP's under CAFRA these are for work Upland of the MHWL in the CAFRA area or out of the CAFRA
    area. This is confusing mistake made when the types of GP's were being assigned in NJEMS. Until we create a new Class Code in NJEMS for coastal GP's we will have this confusion.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_16" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_16">
    m. Ensure waterway is actually a man made lagoon and NOT a man-altered waterway. This would kick the project into an IP and the GP unit doesn't always check. A natural waterway usually has water flowing through it. If the only flow is tide going up and
    down it is usually man made or man altered. Man altered like the Cape May canal needs IP's not GP's. In IMAP pull up the location of the property and using the tidelands layer you can check if the water body is claimed by tidelands then it is natural
    if unclaimed it is man made.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_17" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_17">
    n. If an applicant built a home before CAFRA II 1996 they can subdivide and apply for a GP8 to build a new home. If the home was built or rebuilt under a GP after CAFRA II the second home needs a CAFRA IP.
  </label>
  <br/>
  <input type="checkbox" id="xxxAE27_18" />
  <label for="xxxAE27_18">
    o. All GP's for reconstruction of a single family home if on a dune or along first house on atlantic ocean show be assigned to regions.
  </label>
</fieldset>
